- "Top 10 in salary" refers to the top 10 highest salaries;
- "Contract types" include categories such as full-time, part-time, etc.

- 'cumulative average salary' is the ongoing average salary calculated for each department, adding the average salary of each rank to the previous ranks within the same department;
- 'department' is a division within the university where faculty members are grouped based on their academic or administrative roles;
- 'rank' refers to the position or level of a faculty member within the department, such as assistant professor, associate professor, or full professor.

- 'Stars in the academic sky' refers to faculty members;
- 'Earnings outshine the average glow' refers to salaries greater than the average salary;
- 'List them in the order of their luminous salaries' means the results should be ordered by salary in descending order.

- "seasoned full-time faculty" refers to full-time faculty members with more than 10 years of service;
- "sown their knowledge for more than a decade" refers to years of service > 10;
- "performance has blossomed" refers to performance rating > 4.

- 'full-time' refers to faculty members who work full-time at the university;
- 'years of service' refers to the number of years a faculty member has been employed at the university;
- 'average salary' is the mean salary of the faculty members in each group;
- 'research contributions' are quantified measures of the faculty member's research output or impact.

- "More than 5 years of service" implies the faculty member has been at the university for at least 6 years;
- "High performance rating" is defined as a performance rating greater than 80;
- "Minimum salary for their rank" indicates the salary must meet or exceed the minimum salary defined for the faculty's rank.

sql:
SELECT first_name, last_name
FROM faculty
WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM faculty);

SELECT first_name, performance_rating
FROM faculty
ORDER BY performance_rating DESC;

